An Introduction to Supervised Learning

Ryan Miller

Supervised Learning

  • In supervised learning we use a set of features \(\mathbf{X} = \{X_1,X_2,\ldots,X_p\}\) to model or predict an outcome variable \(Y\), this can be expressed mathematically using the model: \[Y = f(\mathbf{X}) + \epsilon\]
  • Here \(f\) is a fixed but unknown function of the data, and \(\epsilon\) is a random error term
    • \(f\) describes the systematic relationship between the variables in \(\mathbf{X}\) and \(Y\)

Estimating \(f\)

  • Because \(f\) is unknown we must estimate it via \(\hat{f}\), there are two motivating reasons for estimating \(f\):
    • Prediction, if \(Y\) is difficult to obtain but \(\mathbf{X}\) is readily available we can use \(\hat{Y} = \hat{f}(X)\) as an estimate
    • Inference, how \(Y\) is affected by changes in \(\mathbf{X}\) can be understood by studying \(\hat{f}\)
  • How we estimate \(f\) is the fundamental question in machine learning
    • Broadly speaking, there are two major approaches to this: parametric and non-parametric models

Parametric vs.Non-parametric Models

  • Non-parametric models make no explicit assumptions about the functional form of \(f\) and are instead guided by an algorithm aimed at producing an estimate \(\hat{f}\) that is close to \(f\) (but not overfit)
  • In contrast, parametric models impose a structure on the functional form of \(f\), the most widely-known structure is the linear regression model: \[ f(\mathbf{X}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{1} + \beta_2X_2 + \ldots + \beta_pX_p + \epsilon\]
  • By imposing this structure, weve simplified the supervised learning question from estimating some arbitrary \(p\)-dimensional function to estimating a set of regression coefficients, \(\{\beta_0, \beta_1, \ldots, \beta_p\}\)
    • The tradeoff for this simplification is that the models structure might not be flexible enough to accurately reflect patterns in the data

Model Training

  • Making use of a parametric model requires two steps:
    • Specifying the parametric form of the model, ie: deciding \(f(\mathbf{X})\) is a linear combination of \(X_1, X_2, \ldots\)
    • Training or fitting the model, ie: estimating the regression coefficients, or finding \(\hat{\beta}_0, \hat{\beta}_1, \ldots\)

Model Training

  • How a model is trained is crucially important
  • Consider the parametric model \(f(\mathbf{X}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{1} + \epsilon\)
    • There are infinitely many possibilities for the coefficients \(\hat{\beta}_0\) and \(\hat{\beta}_1\) that satisfy this parametric form, but most of them are not good models of \(f\)
    • Shown below are 200 randomly chosen linear models relating \(X\) and \(Y\)

Model Evaluation

  • In order to determine whether a model is good we need an objective measure of its performance
    • A logical approach is to measure the distance between the models predictions (\(\hat{Y}\)) and the observed values of \(Y\)
  • In this class we will focus on two measures (for numeric outcomes), Root Mean Squared Error (\(RMSE\)) and Mean Absolute Error (\(MAE\)): \[RMSE = \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{n}\sum_i (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2} \qquad MAE = \tfrac{1}{n}\sum_i|y_i - \hat{y}_i|\]
  • The plot below displays the 10 models (from the 200 shown on the previous slide) with the lowest \(RMSE\):

Model Training - Revisited

  • Randomly choosing values to use as estimates of \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) is an extremely inefficient method for finding a good model
  • In this class well consider two types of estimates for linear regression models
    • Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) estimates, which are found minimizing \(RMSE\)
    • Least absolute shrinkage and selection operator (LASSO) estimates, which are found by minimizing \(RMSE\) subject to a constraint on the total size of the coefficients: \(\sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_j| \leq s\), an approach known as regularization

Why Regularize?

  • To illustrate the value of regularization, consider the following simulated example:
n <- 300
x <- runif(n,10,20)
y <- 2*x + rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 6)

## Using x as a predictor we can get an RMSE of ~0.35
fit <- lm(y ~ x)
(1/n)*sqrt(sum((y - fit$fitted.values)^2))
## [1] 0.3594849
## Add 100 predictors with no relationship to Y
X <- matrix(rnorm(n*100), n, 100)
newX <- cbind(x, X)
colnames(newX) <- c("x", paste0("FakeVar", 1:100))

## The RMSE has dropped to ~0.29, this is a much better model!
fit <- lm(y ~ newX)
(1/n)*sqrt(sum((y - fit$fitted.values)^2))
## [1] 0.3000532
  • Adding 100 fake predictors having no real relationship with \(Y\) ends up reducing models RMSE (overfitting)

Why Regularize?

  • Fortunately, the LASSO can zero-out most of the fake predictors, leading to a sparse set of regression estimates (and an RMSE similar to the OLS model using only the real \(x\))
library(glmnet)

## Fit lasso model
lassofit <- cv.glmnet(y = y, x = newX)

## Calculate RMSE
(1/n)*sqrt(sum((y - predict(lassofit, newx = newX, s = lassofit$lambda.min))^2))
## [1] 0.3552817
## Look at coefficients
coef(lassofit, s = lassofit$lambda.min)

Out-of-sample vs.In-sample performance

  • The previous example demonstrates the flaw in relying on in-sample RMSE, adding complexity to the model will cause the model to better fit the sample data
  • In the most applications we are interested in out-of-sample performance, or how well the model will generalize to new data that wasnt used in the training process
    • Cross-validation is a method for estimating out-of-sample model performance

Cross-Validation

  • Cross-validation works by using different subsets of data to fit the model (ie: estimate \(\hat{f}\)) and evaluate its predictions
  • We will focus on k-fold cross-validation, which uses the following algorithm:
  1. Randomly divide the original data into \(k\) equally sized, non-overlapping subsets
  2. Fit the candidate model using data from \(k - 1\) folds, then find the models prediction error on the \(k^{th}\) fold (the left out fold)
  3. Repeat step two a total of \(k\) times until each fold has been left out

Image from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-validation_(statistics)

Conclusion

  • This weeks lab will focus on using variants of linear regression to model numeric outcomes
  • It will introduce the caret package as a tool for comparing different models in unified framework using cross-validation
    • Throughout the remainder of the course we will introduce a variety of new models and performance metrics that are implemented in the caret package
